commit 0fa200fb741d47f8f90977750f5718cbb3ce613e
Author: f4alt <christopherjmacgregor@gmail.com>
Date:   Wed Feb 18 10:03:20 2026 -0500

    be a little more memory friendly
    
    There's no reason to always allocate valid_faces array during prep.
    Instead take a two-loop approach: the first pass assumes all faces are
    valid and computes centroids + bounds directly. If an invalid face is
    encountered, we enter a 'heavier' path where we then create the valid
    face mapping to compact the array (skip the bad data).
    
    This preserves crash resilience while reducing memory usage for the
    "correct" usage of bots with good data.

commit 56a6640cb9eb1443103011c8e8cc9718fb585061
Author: f4alt <christopherjmacgregor@gmail.com>
Date:   Thu Feb 12 12:51:06 2026 -0500

    better safeguards on bot prep
    
    Josh caught a bot that crashes when raytraced. So, add a safety function
    to protect prep from doing vector math on bad data (nan's / inf's).
    Might have gotten a bit carried away with the validation checks -
    performance impact is currently untested.
    
    In the future, we could be smarter about stitching out the bad data, but
    this edit matches old (< 7.42.0) behavior of just ignoring the problem
    geometry and moving on to ray tracing.

